{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529669"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:57:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:57:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14441"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14441"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0.72,0.02,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7136"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89617"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43527"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of paranoid delusions and auditory hallucinations. She has no previous psychiatric history. Her parent reports that she has been complaining of joint pain, fatigue, and a facial rash for the past three months. She does not take any regular medications, and has a past history of cannabis usage - though the patient is unwilling to share how much she uses. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears agitated with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 98 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 3.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 110 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 110 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis: 2+ protein\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following initial investigations is most likely to suggest the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brain MRI","Lumbar puncture","Antinuclear antibody (ANA) test","Thyroid function tests","Urine drug screen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with new-onset psychosis in the context of symptoms and laboratory findings suggestive of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). The most appropriate investigation likely to prompt a diagnosis is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eantinuclear antibody (ANA) test\u003C/strong\u003E. A positive ANA test, along with the clinical presentation, would strongly support the diagnosis of SLE-induced psychosis, a neuropsychiatric manifestation of SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrain MRI\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in evaluating neuropsychiatric SLE, it is not the most appropriate first step. MRI findings in SLE-induced psychosis can be normal or show non-specific changes. An MRI would be an appropriate follow-up investigation if the ANA test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in diagnosing central nervous system involvement in SLE, but it is more invasive and less specific than an ANA test as an initial diagnostic step. It might be considered later in the diagnostic process if there is suspicion of CNS infection or other complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are important to rule out thyroid disorders, which can present with psychiatric symptoms. However, given the constellation of symptoms suggestive of SLE (joint pain, fatigue, malar rash, cytopenias, proteinuria), an ANA test is more likely to yield a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine drug screen\u003C/strong\u003E is often performed in cases of new-onset psychosis to rule out substance-induced psychotic disorder. It is a very reasonable investigation - however, would not be the most appropriate option to confirm the suspected diagnosis. The presence of systemic symptoms and laboratory abnormalities make SLE a more likely diagnosis in this case. While cannabis use can lead to psychosis, it is less commonly associated with systemic symptoms experienced by the patient (joint pain, fatigue and facial rash) and laboratory findings seen here, such as joint pain, fatigue, rash, cytopenias, and proteinuria. Therefore, the likelihood of cannabis-induced psychosis being the primary cause is lower compared to SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESLE-induced psychosis is a serious manifestation of SLE that requires prompt diagnosis and treatment. The presence of other SLE symptoms (joint pain, fatigue, malar rash), laboratory abnormalities (cytopenias, proteinuria), and the absence of a previous psychiatric history should raise suspicion for SLE as the underlying cause of psychosis. A positive ANA test, followed by more specific autoantibody tests (such as anti-dsDNA and anti-Smith antibodies), can help confirm the diagnosis of SLE. Early recognition and treatment with immunosuppressive therapy and antipsychotic medications are crucial to prevent long-term neurological complications and improve outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SLE-induced psychosis is a neuropsychiatric manifestation of systemic lupus erythematosus that requires careful differentiation from primary psychiatric disorders.","The presence of other SLE symptoms, positive autoantibodies, and abnormal neuroimaging can help distinguish SLE-induced psychosis from primary psychiatric disorders.","Early recognition and treatment of SLE-induced psychosis is crucial to prevent long-term neurological complications."],"references":["Abrol E, Coutinho E, Chou M, Hart M, Vincent A, Howard R, Zandi MS, Isenberg D. Psychosis in systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE): 40-year experience of a specialist centre. Rheumatology. 2021 Dec 1;60(12):5620-9."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89617"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14441"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89617"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T17:47:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T17:47:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7136"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},